   "source": [
    "(1) Import the global air temperature data set and familiarize yourself with it. Whatâ€™s the temporal resolution? Which longitudes and latitudes are covered by this data? Which time period is covered? Visualize global air temperatures (averaged over the full time period) using Basemap. (3P)\n",
    "\n",
    "(2) Compute anomalies, i.e. detrend each time series by subtracting the respective seasonal variation. Why is this an important pre-processing procedure? Is there a trend left in the resulting temperature anomalies? (2P)\n",
    "\n",
    "(3) Generate an adjacency matrix to obtain a network representation of global air temperature anomalies over the full period of time. In particular, compute pairwise linear correlations between all anomaly time series and apply a threshold to the correlation matrix such that the resulting network has a density of 5%. Discard all self-links. Plot & discuss the resulting adjacency matrix. (6P)\n",
    "\n",
    "(4) Compute the degree of each node using the networkx degree-attribute. Reshape it such that it can be plotted on the world map. (3P)\n",
    "\n",
    "(5) Compute & visualize the area weighted connectivity field of global air temperature anomalies. To do so, implement a function that returns the area weighted connectivity of a node (without using the networkx node-attribute). Use Basemap to visualize it and to compare the node degrees (from 4) to the area weighted connectivity field. (8P)\n",
    "\n",
    "(6) Are there links between temperature anomalies of very distant regions? Compute the geographical distribution of link lengths (in km) between all nodes in the global air temperature anomaly network. Plot the distribution with log-log-scale. Also plot the average geographical link length of each node using Basemap. Interpret your findings. (8P)"
   ]

    "# (1) import the file\n",
    "\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import numpy.ma as ma\n",

    "\n",
    "warnings.filterwarnings(\"ignore\",category=matplotlib.cbook.mplDeprecation)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "from netCDF4 import Dataset\n",
    "from netcdf_description import ncdump\n",
    "\n",
    "# import the data set\n",
    "\n",
    "nc_fid=Dataset(\"air.mon.mean.nc\",'r')\n",
    "\n",
    "# information on the data set\n",
    "\n",
    "nc_attrs, nc_dims, nc_vars = ncdump(nc_fid)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Longitudes from 0 to 357.5 and latitudes from 90 to -90 are covered. The temporal resolution is monthly and the time range is from 1948 until present."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# extract the data from the netcdf file\n",
    "\n",
    "a_lat = ma.getdata(nc_fid.variables['lat'][:])\n",
    "a_lon = ma.getdata(nc_fid.variables['lon'][:])\n",
    "a_temp = ma.getdata(nc_fid.variables['air'][:])"
   ]

   ],
   "source": [
    "# the air temperature is stored in ax0=time (months), ax1 = latitude, ax2 = longitutde\n",
    "\n",
    "a_temp.shape"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# calculate the mean over the full time period\n",
    "\n",
    "a_temp_mean = np.mean(a_temp, axis=0)"

    "lons,lats= np.meshgrid(a_lon,a_lat)\n",

   "source": [
    "# (2) compute anomalies\n",
    "\n",
    "# flatten the array to simplify the calculations\n",
    "\n",
    "a_flatten = np.moveaxis(a_temp,0,-1)\n",
    "a_flatten = a_flatten.reshape((144*73, 876))\n",
    "\n",
    "a_flatten.shape"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# for each pixel ...\n",
    "\n",
    "for i in range(a_flatten.shape[0]):\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # ... substract the longterm mean of each month over the years from each month\n",
    "    \n",
    "    for month in range(12):\n",
    "        \n",
    "        a_flatten[i][month::12] = a_flatten[i][month::12] - np.mean(a_flatten[i][month::12])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "(876, 144, 73)"
      ]

     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# reshape the array to match the original dimensions\n",
    "\n",
    "a_anomaly = a_flatten.reshape((144, 73, 876))\n",
    "a_anomaly= np.moveaxis(a_anomaly,2,0)\n",
    "a_anomaly.shape"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "code",

   "source": [
    "# extract one pixel to see if it worked\n",

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This is an important pre-processing procedure to explore the time series as we lose some information while seasonal adjustment process, there is a trend but not as visible as it is in seasonal series."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# (3) Generate an adjacency matrix\n",
    "\n",
    "# flatten the anomaly array again to compute the correlations\n",
    "\n",
    "a_flatten = np.moveaxis(a_anomaly,0,-1)\n",
    "a_flatten = a_flatten.reshape((144*73, 876))\n",
    "\n",
    "# compute the correlations\n",
    "\n",
    "a_correlation =np.corrcoef(a_flatten, rowvar = True)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# set all self-links, represented by the main diagonal to 0\n",
    "\n",
    "a_idx = np.diag_indices(a_correlation.shape[0])\n",
    "a_correlation[a_idx] = 0\n",
    "\n",
    "# set the top 5 % correlations to 1, the others to 0\n",
    "\n",
    "a_adj = np.where(a_correlation > np.nanpercentile(a_correlation, 95), 1, 0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",

       "<Figure size 1440x1440 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {

     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# plot the adjacency matrix\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(20,20))\n",
    "plt.imshow(a_adj, origin = 'lower', cmap = 'binary');"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "From the above adjancency matrix, There seem to be 3 main areas. The area in the bottom left corner represents the North Pole, the area in the center represents the region around the equator and the area in the top right corner represents the South Pole. Each area shows correlation within itself, but also to other regions. For example, the North Pole and South Pole show correlation with the equator region too.  "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# (4) Compute the degree of each node\n",
    "\n",
    "import networkx as nx\n",
    "\n",
    "# compute the laplacian matrix from the adjacency matrix\n",
    "\n",
    "G = nx.from_numpy_matrix(a_adj)\n",
    "a_lap = nx.laplacian_matrix(G).toarray()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# extract the main diagonal, which represents the degree of each node\n",
    "\n",
    "a_diag = np.diagonal(a_lap)\n",
    "\n",
    "# reshape the diagonal to match the spatial dimensions\n",
    "\n",
    "a_deg = a_diag.reshape(73,144)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {

    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# plot the result\n",
    "\n",
    "fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,15))\n",
    "m = Basemap(projection ='mill', llcrnrlat=-90,urcrnrlat=90,llcrnrlon=0,urcrnrlon=357.5,resolution='c')\n",
    "\n",
    "lons,lats= np.meshgrid(a_lon,a_lat)\n",
    "x,y = m(lons,lats)\n",
    "\n",
    "m.drawcoastlines()\n",
    "\n",
    "mesh = m.pcolormesh(x, y, a_deg,vmin= np.percentile(a_deg,5) \n",
    "                    , vmax= np.percentile(a_deg,95) )\n",
    "m.drawparallels(a_lat[::6], labels=[1,1,0,1]);\n",
    "m.drawmeridians(a_lon[::10], labels=[1,1,0,1]);\n",
    "\n",
    "cb = m.colorbar(mesh, location = 'bottom', pad=0.5)\n",
    "cb.set_label('Degree', fontsize = 14)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",

   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# (5) Compute & visualize the area weighted connectivity field of global air temperature anomalies\n",
    "\n",
    "# define an AWC function\n",
    "\n",
    "def awc(array, a_lat):\n",
    "    \n",
    "    a_coslats = np.cos(np.radians(a_lat))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    res = (array.T*a_coslats)/np.sum(a_coslats)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    return res.T"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# calculate the AWC of the degree array\n",
    "\n",
    "a_deg_awc = awc(a_deg, a_lat)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",

    "\n",
    "lons,lats= np.meshgrid(a_lon,a_lat)\n",
    "x,y = m(lons,lats)\n",
    "\n",
    "m.drawcoastlines()\n",
    "\n",
    "mesh = m.pcolormesh(x, y, a_deg_awc, vmin= np.percentile(a_deg_awc,5) \n",
    "                    , vmax= np.percentile(a_deg_awc,95) )\n",
    "m.drawparallels(a_lat[::6], labels=[1,1,0,1]);\n",
    "m.drawmeridians(a_lon[::10], labels=[1,1,0,1]);\n",
    "\n",
    "cb = m.colorbar(mesh, location = 'bottom', pad=0.5)\n",
    "cb.set_label('Area weighted connectivity', fontsize = 14)"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The intensity in the polar regions decreased and remained constant in the equator area."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# (6) Compute the geographical distribution of link lengths (in km) \n",
    "# between all nodes in the global air temperature anomaly network. \n",
    "\n",
    "def great_circ_dist(lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2):\n",
    "    # radius of the earth\n",
    "    R = 6373.0\n",
    "    # conversion to radians\n",
    "    lat1, lon1 = math.radians(lat1), math.radians(lon1)\n",
    "    lat2, lon2 = math.radians(lat2), math.radians(lon2)\n",
    "    # distance computation\n",
    "    dlon = lon2 - lon1\n",
    "    dlat = lat2 - lat1\n",
    "    a = math.sin(dlat / 2)**2 + math.cos(lat1) * math.cos(lat2) * math.sin(dlon / 2)**2\n",
    "    # catch rounding errors\n",
    "    if a > 1:\n",
    "        a=1\n",
    "    c = 2 * math.atan2(math.sqrt(a), math.sqrt(1 - a))\n",
    "    distance = R * c\n",
    "    return distance"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 21,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# make a list to store the distances for each node\n",
    "\n",
    "l_dists = []\n",
    "\n",
    "# for each node ..\n",
    "\n",
    "for node in range(a_adj.shape[0]):\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # determine the latitude and the longitude..\n",
    "    idx_node_lat = int(node/144)\n",
    "    idx_node_lon = node-idx_node_lat*144\n",
    "    \n",
    "    lat_node = a_lat[idx_node_lat]\n",
    "    lon_node = a_lon[idx_node_lon]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # find the connected nodes from the adjacency matrix\n",
    "    \n",
    "    connected_nodes_idxs = np.where(a_adj[node,:] == 1)[0]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # make a list to store the distance \n",
    "    \n",
    "    l_dist = []\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # for each connected node..\n",
    "    \n",
    "    for connected_node in connected_nodes_idxs:\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # ..determine latitude and longitute of the connected node..\n",
    "        idx_connected_node_lat = int(connected_node/144)\n",
    "        idx_connected_node_lon = connected_node-idx_connected_node_lat*144\n",
    "    \n",
    "        lat_connected_node = a_lat[idx_connected_node_lat]\n",
    "        lon_connected_node = a_lon[idx_connected_node_lon]\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # ..and calculate the distance from the node to the connected node\n",
    "        \n",
    "        dist = great_circ_dist(lat_node, lon_node, lat_connected_node, lon_connected_node)\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # store the distance in a list\n",
    "        \n",
    "        l_dist.append(dist)\n",
    "        \n",
    "    # store all distances of the node \n",
    "    \n",
    "    l_dists.append(l_dist)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 22,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# dissolve the list of lists for the histogram\n",
    "\n",
    "l_dists_flatten = [l for sublist in l_dists for l in sublist]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 23,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# calculate the the distance frequencies \n",
    "hist, bin_edges = np.histogram(l_dists_flatten, bins = 50)"

  {
   "cell_type": "code",

   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
